{{Refimprove|date=August 28, 2017}} [[File:Fujisan Hongu Sengen okunomiya.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{ill|Okumiya|ja|奥宮|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Fujisan Hongū Sengen Taisha|ja|富士山本宮浅間大社|12=draft|12=draft}} at the summit of {{ill|Mount Fuji|ja|富士山|12=draft|12=draft}}]] '''Okumiya''' (奥宮) refers to a term used in {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|12=draft|12=draft}} for describing the relationship between certain {{ill|Shrine architecture|ja|神社建築|12=draft|12=draft}} buildings at a shrine, or the building itself that holds such a relationship. It is also referred to as '''Okusha''' (奥社) or '''Oku-no-in''' (奥の院).<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%A5%A5%E5%AE%AE-451835|title=奥宮(おくのみや)とは|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=[[Kotobank]]}}</ref>
== Overview == The term is often used when a shrine has multiple buildings, and these buildings are significantly far apart, such that they may appear to be entirely separate shrines. Conversely, the term is rarely used if there is only one building or if multiple buildings are located in close proximity to one another.
A typical usage is when the same {{ill|deity|ja|祭神|12=draft|12=draft}} is enshrined in two locations, such as at the base and the summit of a mountain. In such cases, the shrine at the mountain base (referred to as the main shrine, main sanctuary, or lower shrine) is contrasted with the shrine at the summit, which is referred to as the Okumiya, Okusha, or Kamimiya.<ref name=":0" /> Additionally, there are cases where a main sanctuary was originally located at the mountain summit but was later moved to the base for convenience of worship. The original sanctuary then became the Okumiya, which in such instances may also be called "Motomiya" (元宮).<ref>The {{ill|Hakone Shrine|ja|箱根神社|12=draft|12=draft}} exemplifies this case, with its Okumiya referred to as the Motomiya.</ref>
== Prominent Okumiya == <gallery> 武蔵御岳神社 奥宮.jpg|{{ill|Musashi Mitake Shrine|ja|武蔵御嶽神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Kashimajingu okumiya.jpg|{{ill|Kashima Jingū|ja|鹿島神宮|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Shirayama-okumiya in Hakusan.jpg|{{ill|Shirayama Hime Shrine|ja|白山比咩神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya 太平山神社.jpg|{{ill|Taiheizan Shrine|ja|太平山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Ogamiyamajinja Okunomiya 08.jpg|{{ill|Ōgamiyama Shrine|ja|大神山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Okunomiya of Fushimi Inari Grand Shrine.JPG|{{ill|Fushimi Inari-taisha|ja|伏見稲荷大社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Mitumine005.jpg|{{ill|Mitsumine Shrine|ja|三峯神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Hakone Mount Komagatake shrine Dsc05579.jpg|{{ill|Hakone Shrine|ja|箱根神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya (Motomiya) Top of Mount Hongu 2010-02-27.jpg|{{ill|Ōagata Shrine|ja|大縣神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Mount Owarifujij top 2010-02-27.jpg|{{ill|Ōmiya Sengen Shrine|ja|大宮浅間神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Shinto shrine Kumanohakusangongen 2010-4-4.JPG|{{ill|Nōgo Hakusan Shrine|ja|能郷白山神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Shinto shrine Ena 2008-05-22.jpg|{{ill|Ena Shrine|ja|恵那神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Futenma-gū Cave.JPG|{{ill|Futenma Shrine|ja|普天満宮|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Houtokuinari Nagaoka.jpg|{{ill|Hōtoku Inari Taisha|ja|宝徳山稲荷大社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Toga Shrine - Okumiya.jpg|{{ill|Toga Shrine|ja|砥鹿神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya Kibune7286.jpg|{{ill|Kifune Shrine|ja|貴船神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya 枚岡神社神津嶽本宮.jpg|{{ill|Hiraoka Shrine|ja|枚岡神社|12=draft|12=draft}} Okumiya (Motomiya) </gallery>
