{{Refimprove|date=August 28, 2017}} [[File:Fujisan Hongu Sengen okunomiya.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{ill|Okumiya|ja|奥宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Fujisan Hongū Sengen Taisha|ja|富士山本宮浅間大社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at the summit of {{ill|Mount Fuji|ja|富士山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}]] '''Okumiya''' (奥宮) refers to a term used in {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} for describing the relationship between certain {{ill|Shrine architecture|ja|神社建築|qq=draft|qq=draft}} buildings at a shrine, or the building itself that holds such a relationship. It is also referred to as '''Okusha''' (奥社) or '''Oku-no-in''' (奥の院).<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%A5%A5%E5%AE%AE-451835|title=奥宮(おくのみや)とは|accessdate=2020-04-22|publisher=[[Kotobank]]}}</ref>
== Overview == The term is often used when a shrine has multiple buildings, and these buildings are significantly far apart, such that they may appear to be entirely separate shrines. Conversely, the term is rarely used if there is only one building or if multiple buildings are located in close proximity to one another.
A typical usage is when the same {{ill|deity|ja|祭神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is enshrined in two locations, such as at the base and the summit of a mountain. In such cases, the shrine at the mountain base (referred to as the main shrine, main sanctuary, or lower shrine) is contrasted with the shrine at the summit, which is referred to as the Okumiya, Okusha, or Kamimiya.<ref name=":0" /> Additionally, there are cases where a main sanctuary was originally located at the mountain summit but was later moved to the base for convenience of worship. The original sanctuary then became the Okumiya, which in such instances may also be called "Motomiya" (元宮).<ref>The {{ill|Hakone Shrine|ja|箱根神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} exemplifies this case, with its Okumiya referred to as the Motomiya.</ref>
