== Overview == The term is often used when a shrine has multiple buildings, and these buildings are significantly far apart, such that they may appear to be entirely separate shrines. Conversely, the term is rarely used if there is only one building or if multiple buildings are located in close proximity to one another.
A typical usage is when the same {{ill|deity|ja|祭神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/deity|qq=}} is enshrined in two locations, such as at the base and the summit of a mountain. In such cases, the shrine at the mountain base (referred to as the main shrine, main sanctuary, or lower shrine) is contrasted with the shrine at the summit, which is referred to as the Okumiya, Okusha, or Kamimiya.<ref name=":0" /> Additionally, there are cases where a main sanctuary was originally located at the mountain summit but was later moved to the base for convenience of worship. The original sanctuary then became the Okumiya, which in such instances may also be called "Motomiya" (元宮).<ref>The {{ill|Hakone Shrine|ja|箱根神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakone Shrine|qq=}} exemplifies this case, with its Okumiya referred to as the Motomiya.</ref>
